Guide to analyse Property dataset¶

This guide would be covering all the steps from basics!!
Dataset link: https://github.com/ShivangiSharma77/StatusNeo_Task1/tree/main/data

Hardware and software requirements¶

Hardware requirements:

  • Laptop/Desktop/iMac

Software requirements:

  • Windows operationg system
  • Search Engine
  • Google account

Internet connection a must.

1. Setting up the environment¶

1.1 Switch on your PC by clicking the power button¶

1.2 Connect PC to the internet¶

You can use Wifi to connect your PC to the internet, toggle to the bottom right of the screen and connect to WiFi by clicking on the WiFi icon then selecting your router.

1.3 Open any search engine¶

Double click on the search engine icon ( ex. google chrome)

1.4 Type the following link in the search bar https://colab.research.google.com/notebooks/intro.ipynb#recent=true the link redirects to google collab¶

Type the above link in the search bar given at the top of the screen. Multiple enviornments can be used for data analysis. We would be conducting the analysis on google collab.

1.5 Sign in to google collab¶

Sign in with your gmail account by selecting the blue sign in button at upper right corner.

1.6 Open a new notebook¶

Select new notebook option from File option at the upper left corner.

2. Getting started¶

2.1 Importing the libraries¶

Type the following command into the first cell, for importing the necessary libraries which would be used for data analysis.

In [2]:
import numpy as np
import pandas as pd
import matplotlib.pyplot as plt
import matplotlib.image as mpimg
%matplotlib inline
import seaborn as sns

3. Data loading¶

We need to load the dataset for analysis.

3.1 Importing data files to google collab¶

Now, the necessary files can be uploaded ie. Bangalore.csv Chennai.csv Delhi.csv Hyderabad.csv Kolkata.csv Mumbai.csv from the data folder.

from google.colab import files files.upload()

3.2 Reading the data files¶

All the data files are in csv format. To read the data files we write the following function, which will read the files and store them in a dataframe

In [12]:
def read_data(files):
    return pd.read_csv(files)

Now read the delhi.csv file in df1-

In [15]:
df1 = read_data("Delhi.csv")

4. Data Preprocessing¶

4.1 Adding states column to datasets¶

we can create a new column "States" in all the datasets by adding the repective state. The following function returns the list of state coumn.

In [35]:
def def_state(n,s):
    state=[]
    state += n * [s]
    return state

For delhi's dataset we would make the entire state column as delhi, similarly all states can be added in their dataframes.

In [49]:
res1 = def_state(df1.shape[0],"Delhi")
In [38]:
res2 = def_state(df2.shape[0],"Bangalore")
In [41]:
res3 = def_state(df3.shape[0],"Chennai")
In [44]:
res4 = def_state(df4.shape[0],"Hyderabad")
In [45]:
res5 = def_state(df5.shape[0],"Kolkata")
In [46]:
res6 = def_state(df6.shape[0],"Mumbai")

Now we can make a new column "State" in the data frames.

In [50]:
df1['State'] = res1
In [51]:
df2['State'] = res2
In [52]:
df3['State'] = res3
In [53]:
df4['State'] = res4
In [54]:
df5['State'] = res5
In [55]:
df6['State'] = res6

6.20 Count of columns¶

We can create countplot by any attribute by using the below function

In [170]:
def plots(plot):

    return sns.countplot(data[plot], ax=ax)
